5,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Marotta Staff 2020",Chris Marotta Job 2020 revised.docx,"Job Summary

The Division of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering at the California Institute of Technology (Caltech) is seeking a highly motivated individual for a Research Scientist position involving biomedical materials. The individual is expected to contribute to multidisciplinary projects that include materials applications for diseases of the eye and detection of ovarian cancer. Duties will range from synthesizing up-converting nanoparticles (UCNPs) for bright and selective light emission to designing biocompatible formulations for in vivo fluorescence detection and polymerization. The candidate reports directly to the designated Principal Investigator (PI) at Caltech, but will also collaborate closely with individuals at UCSF, City of Hope, and a start-up company by the designated PI. Most duties and research will be performed at Caltech but occasional travel to the other sites may be required.
Work in collaboration with UCSF to develop formulations for degenerative myopia treatment through generation of singlet oxygen.
Work on the development of polymers for antibacterial and antiviral coatings.
Set up collaborations for testing of materials by outside groups.
Provide initial studies of new technologies to the proof of concept level.
– Serve as project lead by organizing progress report meetings and combining collaborator and PI observations to outline the next milestones for each project.
– Manage intellectual property applications (grants, patents, and manuscripts).
– Prioritize experiments to meet research deadlines on numerous projects.
– Occasional travel to collaborators for progress updates and some experimental data collection.
– Research experience in chemical biology, materials chemistry, and polymer chemistry.

– Expertise in synthesis, characterization, and surface modification of up-converting nanoparticles; particularly in transmission electron microscopy, absorbance/fluorescence spectroscopy, and infra-red spectroscopy.
– Proficiency in writing project updates, grant applications, and patent applications.
– Ability to advance projects simultaneously while prioritizing tasks to meet strict deadlines.
– Experience working in multidisciplinary teams, both as a collaborator and a project lead.
– At least two years postdoctoral experience.
– Small molecule ligand design and synthesis.
– Familiarity with anatomy, diseases, and surgical limitations of the eye.

column1: Division of Chemistry & Chemical Engineering MC: 164-30
RE: Jeong Hoon Ko – Postdoctoral Research Appointment

Jeong Hoon Ko is completing his PhD at UCLA with Professor Heather Maynard.  Ko has an outstanding record of academic success and has completed a very important research project at UCLA.  His background is in the applications of new materials to biological applications.  Maynard and Ken Houk give him their highest recommendations.  In my group, he will be working on projects for the development on materials for medical applications.  We have long standing collaborations in this area and his background is perfect for this research.  In my interview, I was impressed by his enthusiasm and professionalism.  He is in the process of applying for support for his stay, however, his appointment does not depend on his success in securing a postdoctoral fellowship.

20,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Guzman postdoc 2013",Application Information for Guzman.docx,"Applications must be prepared using the PHS 398 research grant application forms. Applications must have a Dun and Bradstreet (D&B) Data Universal Numbering System (DUNS) number as the universal identifier when applying for Federal grants or cooperative agreements. The D&B number can be obtained by calling (866) 705-5711 or through the web site at http://www.dnb.com. The D&B number should be entered on the face page of the PHS 398 form.
See Section VI.2 for additional information.
The title and number of this funding opportunity must be typed in item (box) 2 only of the face page of the application form and the YES box must be checked.

A request for a supplement may be submitted at any time. In making requests, the grantee institution, on behalf of the Principal Investigator of the parent grant and in cooperation with the candidate must submit the request for supplemental funds directly to the awarding component that supports the parent grant. The request should not be submitted to the NIH Center for Scientific Review. The Principal Investigator must submit one original and two copies of the application to the address listed under the appropriate awarding component under Agency Contacts in Section VII.1 (http://grants.nih.gov/grants/guide/contacts/PA-08-190_contacts.htm).
The request for a supplemental award must include the following:

A completed face page (with appropriate signatures) from Grant Application Form PHS 398. Include the title and grant number of the parent grant and the name Research Supplements to Promote Diversity in Health-Related Research.
A brief, six-page description, prepared by the Principal Investigator of the parent grant that includes:
A summary or abstract of the funded grant or project.
A plan and timeline for the research and career development experiences proposed for the candidate.

A description of how the research and career development experiences will expand and foster the research capabilities of the candidate; how the proposed experiences relates to the specific research goals and objectives of the parent grant; and a description of the mentorship that will be provided.

Also, in addition to the research plan, it is important to have a well-developed, personalized career development training plan for the candidate, and to describe plans for obtaining alternative support to take over after the supplement.

A biographical sketch of the candidate, not to exceed 4 pages, that includes evidence of scientific achievement or interest. The source of current funding must also be listed. Include the following in the biosketch:

Social Security Number of the candidate. (Per NOT-OD-09-093 issued on May 7, 2009, ONLY the last 4 digits of the Social Security Number of the candidate are now required) (The PHS uses the Social Security Number for the purpose of accurate identification, referral, and review of applications and for efficient management of PHS grant programs. Although provision of the Social Security Number is voluntary, it will facilitate the processing of applications for supplements.)
A signed statement from the candidate outlining her/his research objectives and career goals.

A signed statement from the Principal Investigator and an institutional official establishing the eligibility of the candidate for support under this program. The statement must include clearly presented information on citizenship. The statement must also include a convincing description of how the appointment of this specific candidate will address the issue of diversity within the national scientific workforce or within the workforce or the relevant population at the grantee institution (see Section I: Recruitment and Retention to Enhance Diversity). Finally, the statement must additionally describe any current or previous PHS research grant support the candidate has received. The strength of this statement will be considered by the NIH administrative review committee along with all other material provided.

A proposed budget entered on budget pages from Grant Application Form PHS 398, related to the percent effort (where appropriate) for the research experience of the candidate during the first and future years. If the initial budget period requested is less than 12 months, the budget must be prorated accordingly.

Documentation, if applicable, that the proposed research experience was approved by the Institutional Animal Care and Use Committee (IACUC) or human subjects Institutional Review Board (IRB) at the grantee institution must be provided. Adherence to the NIH policy for including women and minorities in clinical studies must also be insured if additional human subjects' involvement is planned for the supplement component.
A copy of the most recent official transcript if the candidate is a high school, undergraduate, post-baccalaureate degree, post-master's degree, or graduate student.

If the candidate is a student at another institution during the academic year, the application must include an appropriately signed letter from a responsible official at the institution of matriculation indicating that participation at the stated level of effort is approved and will not detract from or interfere with the student's course of studies.

If any of the research is to be conducted at a site other than the grantee institution, an appropriately signed letter from the institution where the research is to be conducted must be submitted. The request must be signed by the candidate, the Principal Investigator, and the appropriate institutional business official.

If the request is for a supplement based on disability, the institution should indicate what, if any, reasonable accommodations the institution has supported or plans to provide along with a full description of how any additional support for accommodation might be used. The relationship of the proposed accommodation to the proposed project must be described.
21,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Guzman postdoc 2013/Guzman NIH pages copy",Description.docx,"Supplement Description

column2: A summary or abstract of the funded grant or project.

column1: The synthesis of complex molecules such as those used in pharmaceuticals depends heavily on the ability to rapidly and efficiently construct carbon-carbon bonds.  Over the past decades, olefin metathesis has become a key tool for such a process.  Olefin metathesis has been used widely in drug discovery and is now moving into process chemistry.  A number of pharmaceutical agents that are made possible by the metathesis reaction have proceeded through Phase II trials and a number are now entering into Phase III.

Although the olefin metathesis reaction has been known for a number of decades, it has only become useful in organic synthesis with the discovery of highly active and stable catalysts that are tolerant of most functional groups and are easily used by organic chemists.  The modification of ligands on the basic ruthenium-based metathesis complexes has resulted in highly efficient catalysts that are used in a wide array of applications, from pharmaceutical synthesis to the construction of high-end composites.  Each advance in catalyst efficiency and selectivity has opened a variety of new applications.  One of the final deficiencies in catalyst design has been the lack of control of double bond geometry.  In most cases, the reactions produce a majority of the more stable E geometric isomer.  During the last granting period, major breakthroughs have been made in the design of catalyst that will produce Z-olefins in high yields from simple terminal olefins.  These catalysts open many new applications.  During the next granting period, efforts will be made to increase their efficiency and selectivity, and to develop applications that exploit their capabilities.  Building on the lessons from the discovery of a Z-selective catalyst, new systems will be designed that will be focused on the synthesis of purely E-olefins.  The results from the next granting period will further enhance the utility of the powerful olefin metathesis reaction in the synthesis of new pharmaceuticals and bioactive molecules.

column2: A plan and timeline for the research and career development experiences proposed for the candidate.

column1: It is anticipated that Dr. Guzman will start his postdoctoral work at Caltech in the fall of 2013.  During the first month of his time he will be trained in the safety standards of our research group.  All group members go through a thorough training in safety.  This is an important aspect of training for a future career.  He will also become familiar with all aspects of the research in the group and we will mutually decide on the exact project in the area of olefin metathesis catalyst development that he will explore.  During the early stages of his time at Caltech, he will focus on getting a research project underway and learning to fit into the environment in the group.  It is important for the candidate to be a co-author on an early publication.  In the second half of the first year, I will start to involve him in some of the management aspects of the group such as paper editing and proposal writing.  In the second year, I will involve him the management of small groups of researchers working in his area.  This will involve an undergraduate researcher involved in our SURF program for summer undergraduate researchers.  In many cases, these students continue throughout the year on a more limited basis.  Also during this period, he will be involved in group meetings where members of the group who are applying for jobs discuss their research plans. Since in most years, at least one member of the group leaves for a position at a top University; this practice is particularly valuable in training him for his own application process.  During his last year, I will encourage him to continue his involvement in all aspects of group management as well as to start the early exploration of research areas that he has chosen for his independent career.  I have found in the past that this practice provides a fast start for new faculty in their new positions.
During his complete stay at Caltech, he will attend divisional research seminars, attend ACS meetings and take part in all research group meetings.

After completion of the supplement funding, the PI has funds available from industry, such as Elevance Renewable Sciences, that are unrestricted but will be used for the development of advanced metathesis catalysts of the type he will be exploring.

column2: A description of how the research and career development experiences will expand and foster the research capabilities of the candidate; how the proposed experiences relates to the specific research goals and objectives of the parent grant; and a description of the mentorship that will be provided.

column1: Dr. Guzman will be part of a research group that has produced over 75 faculty members over the past 4 decades.  The environment of the group fosters close interaction among the graduate students and postdoctoral fellows.  The practices that have led to success in these cases involve the involvement in proposal and paper writing, informal discussions and planning of research, regular group meetings where a broad array of research is presented. Caltech provides a stimulating environment that encourages interdisciplinary research and the choice of tough and important problems.

Dr. Guzman will work on a part of the NIH project that is directed toward the preparation of selective organometallic catalysts.  The exact project will depend on the state of the research when he arrives and his preferences.  The work will be a combination of catalyst synthesis and the development of applications for new catalysts to demonstrate their specific features and the opportunities they present.   His background in synthesis and the development of new reactivity will be particularly valuable.  In the above section, a schedule and plan was presented for training in all aspects of research management.  As in the past, the regular discussions between the PI and the postdoctoral fellow will help provide direction based on the PI’s past experience in helping postdoctoral transition into their own independent careers.

column2: Evidence of adequate mentoring experience and success.

column1: Over the past 46 years, over 75 students and postdoctoral fellows have moved from the PI’s group into academic positions.  Many of the other students and postdoctoral fellows, around 200, are now major players in industrial research and management.  Of the over 70 students and postdoctoral fellows who have accepted academic positions, only 2 did not become tenured professors.  The other 2 have had outstanding careers in industry.  The same practices that produced these successes are still in place.  There is a particularly talented group of postdoctoral fellows presently in the group.  They are extremely interactive and their interactions and experiences will supplement the mentoring process.

column2: Evidence that the candidate will receive research career mentoring.

column1: The PI will have regular meetings with the candidate and will use the same strategies that have resulted in successful training periods in the past as demonstrated by the former postdoctoral fellows who have progress through the program to successful positions.

Division of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering, 164-30
Victor and Elizabeth Atkins Professor of Chemistry
Arnold and Mabel Beckman Laboratories of Chemical Synthesis

column2: As a Professor of the California Institute of Technology, I am pleased to invite you to participate as a Guest (Student) in order to conduct research at the California Institute of Technology located in Pasadena, California, USA. This invitation is effective for four weeks starting July 7, 2014.

Although we can work together to determine your exact project closer to you arrival, as a part of my group you will have the opportunity to conduct research under the supervision of Dr. Pablo E. Guzmán, a Postdoctoral Researcher. Working with Dr. Guzmán, your research will center on synthesizing, characterizing, and optimizing Z-selective cross metathesis reactions directed towards the total synthesis of Aliskiren. The guest does not incur any tuition or fees. This status is a non-degree program and provides research training only, enrollment in courses is not permitted and therefore no additional fees would be applied. There is no endorsement of joint or dual degree status with the California Institute of Technology.

column1: Guests or Visiting Student Researchers are not covered by health insurance under the Caltech plan, so you will need to provide proof of comparable health and accident insurance for the duration of your stay. Also note that under this status, you are not eligible for Caltech stipend or housing and should allow for adequate funds to cover your housing and living expensed during your stay at Caltech.
28,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Boyd VSR_UG 2014",Draft Lucinda Boyd Award Letter.docx,"To Whom it May Concern:
We are pleased to announce that The Center for STEM Education and Research (CSER) has awarded Lucinda Boyd an opportunity to study at The California Institute of Technology.

Ms. Boyd will spend three weeks during the month of July performing research at Caltech.  The amount of the award includes all travel expenses. Ms. Boyd has the necessary health and liability insurance for her visit.  As well, CSER will provide a stipend of $400 per week ($1,200 total), travel to and from Los Angeles plus room and board and other miscellaneous expenses.

The Center for STEM Education and Research is committed to increasing the talent pool for underrepresented minorities in the STEM workforce. Our mission and programs focus on providing opportunities for personal and professional growth for students, faculty and community members through education, mentoring and scholarship.
We are proud to offer Ms. Lucinda Boyd this award to further her academic career and enhance her knowledge of STEM through our network of dedicated professionals.
If you have any questions regarding Ms. Boyd, CSER or this award, please feel free to contact me directly at 773-995-2965 or ljones27@csu.edu.
Professor of Chemistry & Director for STEM Initiatives
Executive Director, Center for STEM Education & Research

31,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Hartung PDS 2012/Hartung NRSA",Section II - Sponsor hartung.docx,"Section II--Sponsor and Co-Sponsor Information
Total pre- and postdoctoral individuals previously sponsored: 225
c. Training Plan, Environment, Research Facilities

John Hartung has outstanding recommendations from his PhD advisors- Danishefsky and Norton. He has been involved in total synthesis as well as methods development.  He appears to be a well-rounded chemist who will thrive in the environment at Caltech. Since a number of Caltech students and postdoctoral fellows obtain academic positions, he will have a chance to make contacts that will be valuable as they starts their own academic career.  He will be working in an environment that has produced a significant number of successful academic and industrial scientists over the past several years. Over 70 coworkers from the sponsor’s laboratory have become assistant professors.  Many are in major institutions.

Postdocs will attend seminars given by a large group of international speakers, as well as, take part in departmental and group seminars.  During the winter term, he will attend classes in polymer and organometallic chemistry to expand his background in these areas. The broader group will expose him to research ranging from new NMR techniques to the development of new materials for biomedical applications.  This broad exposure will open a variety of new possibilities -ranging from materials synthesis to new methods development- for him as he starts his independent career.

The laboratories at Caltech are well equipped for the proposed research.  The Grubbs group currently occupies laboratory space with 22 fume hoods and maintains a high level of equipment including gel-permeation chromatographs, dry boxes, centrifuges, and vacuum lines.  In addition, the Department maintains and staffs several instruments that will be essential for the work.  These include 300-600 mHz NMR spectrometers, a fully staffed mass spectroscopy facility (including MALDI, ESI, and various HRMS) and a complete polymer characterization laboratory.  The facilities in the Materials Resource center in the Beckman Institute will also provided needed instrumentation.
d. Number of Fellows/Trainees to be Supervised During the Fellowship
The Grubbs laboratory currently consists of 10 postdoctoral members and 10 Ph.D. students, and is expected to decrease slightly over the next several years.
e. Applicant's Qualifications and Potential for a Research Career

John Hartung has an outstanding record of achievement at Columbia. At Columbia, he has worked in the Danishefsky and Norton laboratories.  They both give him outstanding recommendations for work in their areas of expertise.  He appears to be equally at ease in a total synthesis environment as well as a traditional organometallic/catalysis laboratory. I only accepted him after special lobbying from Sam.  He is really high on this guy and Sam has an excellent track record of producing outstanding students.  In my group he will join a team that is developing new methods for the catalytic conversion of organic molecules.  He will build on the work we have accomplished in the past using chiral metathesis catalysts but with the new insight we have gained from the recent developments in Z selective catalysts. We have examined the desymmetrization strategy for dienes in the past with little success.  With the new insights and synthetic strategies, we hope that this reaction with very high potential can be successful. He appears to have the exact set of skills and the proven track record to accomplish this important goal.
32,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Hartung PDS 2012/Hartung NRSA",Data_Management.docx,"Data Management Plan
The proposed research will produce data in the form of NMR, IR, and UV-Vis spectra, hand written description of experiments in laboratory notebooks, student thesis, and x-ray structural data.

The NMR spectral data is produced both in hard copy and as files on spectrometers that are transferred to the server in the research group. These files are also kept on separate servers maintained by the NMR facility. The laboratory notebooks contain hand written notes from the time of the experiment and in some cases data that is copied and pasted into the notebook.  The x-ray structural data is collected on the individual instrument file and then converted into typed tables and word documents that describe the important parameters.  The X-ray center produces a written report (word file) on each structure completed.
Access to Data and Data Sharing Practices and Policies

The data is made available to interested parties through publications and supplemental data that is published with the manuscript.  Crystal structural data is posted on the Cambridge database for easy access of interested parties.  In cases where there is potential for the generation of intellectual property, the data is compiled and filed as a provisional patent.  Interested parties that desire more information normally contact the PI with specific questions.
Data is not released on a web site, only through supplemental data in publications and through personal contact.

Data that is obtained in electronic form, such as spectra and crystal structures, is stored on the group server in generally readable form.  Written reports, slides and student thesis are stored on the same file saver.  It is backed up by the central institute system.  Written reports, hard copies of spectra and laboratory notebooks are stored in the group files and will be kept indefinitely.  Each student thesis is filed in the Institute library. The broader group will expose her to research ranging from new NMR techniques to the development of new materials for biomedical applications. e. Applicant's Qualifications and Potential for a Research Career

Sarah Bronner has an outstanding record of achievement.  After exploring a number of different areas of science and engineering, she has focused on organic chemistry and specifically organic synthesis and related mechanistic studies.  Professor Garg gives her his highest recommendation.  The work she has completed as a graduate student shows her breadth- both synthesis and mechanisms.  Her program has been an interesting mix of mechanistic studies, theory and applications.  She appears to have the breadth of abilities to make major contributions in al these areas.  We have initiated a collaborative program to develop computational methods to test ideas before synthesis.  She has the perfect back ground to help us is this approach.  I have heard Garg talk about her work and it is outstanding.  In my group she will join a team that is developing new methods for the catalytic conversion of organic molecules.  She has shown the ability to move into new areas and to start new projects.  This will be particularly important for the project she has chosen. We have made progress in the area, but I think a new approach is needed to reach our goals.  She appears to have exactly the skill set we need to make progress in the design on new approaches to the hydration of olefins.
34,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Hartung PDS 2012/Hartung NRSA",Responsible Conduct of Research.docx,"Responsible Conduct of Research

The Caltech Honor System is embodied by the phrase “No member shall take unfair advantage of any member of the Caltech community” and is the fundamental principle of conduct for all students. It is the code of behavior governing scholastic and extracurricular activities, relations among students, and relations between students and faculty. The Conduct Review Committee, composed of student, faculty, and staff, considers cases involving the honor system and institute policies. It conducts investigations and hearing with strict confidentiality, and if necessary, recommendations for actions are made to the deans.

The Grubbs group is committed to the highest levels of ethical standards. Discussions with Professor Grubbs and other group members at weekly meetings will ensure ethical practices are being carried out in the laboratory. Furthermore, a one-term course is offered and recommended at Caltech that discusses many ethical issues in science (Bi 252 – Responsible Conduct of Research) and ensures the awareness of potential ethical pitfalls. Topics include guidelines and regulations, ethical and moral issues, research misconduct, data management and analysis, research with animal or human subjects, publication, conflicts of interest, mentoring, and professional advancement.",1324,"[-1.84470147e-01  1.05396307e+00  7.57572174e-01  2.71554887e-01

It is my great pleasure to invite you in a sabbatical research position in my group for one year starting from Sep. 2019 to Aug. 2020.

The research that you are going to carry out in my group, which is the development of new N-heterocyclic carbene based redox reagents, is very interesting. My long experience of N-heterocyclic carbene definitely helps you to develop such interesting NHC based reagents. Therefore, I believe that our collaboration on N-heterocyclic carbene will helps the utilization of new N-heterocyclic carbene toward the development of novel redox reagents, and their application toward diverse fields including organic chemistry and materials science.
For documentation works, my assistant (lclark@caltech.edu) can help you in addition to finding housing etc.
If there is other question, feel free to contact me.
Victor and Elizabeth Atkins Professor of Chemistry
Division of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering

Harry Lee will assist in developing a degradable polymer adhesive for surgical applications. The Grubbs lab has developed a polymer adhesive that is being explored for eye surgery. In the long term, it will be desirable to imbue degradability to this material. For this project, the cyclic ketene acetal chemistry will be applied to the polymer adhesive to incorporate hydrolytically degradable ester bonds in the polymer backbone such that the adhesive will slowly degrade over several months.

He will be mentored in the lab by a postdoc (Jeong Hoon Ko) and back-up mentor postdoc (Willie Wolf) and will learn small molecule synthesis, polymerization methods, Schlenk line technique, and other laboratory skills. He will also learn how to critically evaluate literature to design his experiments and interpret results.

46,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Lee - Volunteer Summer Student 2019/CWL Volunteer 2019",Selecting and Engaging Caltech Volunteer.docx,"Selecting and Engaging Caltech Volunteer

It is the Division or Department’s responsibility to be certain the individuals being selected as volunteers have adequate experience, qualifications and training, including requisite safety instructions for the tasks they will perform. The following procedures are suggested to ensure that your selection process is successful.
Determine if an Oracle record and therefore other forms are required.
If no agreement is required, maintain the Volunteer Data Sheet in your Division/Department (for your information and for Workers Compensation).
If an Oracle record is needed and therefore other documents are required, have the prospective volunteer and the Division/Department complete all of the remaining forms.

Individuals under 18 years of age may only volunteer for services appropriate to their age and skill level and with the appropriate work permit from their school. The Volunteer Agreement for Minors must be completed in addition to the other forms(View Minor Volunteer Guidlines).
Forward completed forms to Human Resources (MC 153-84) for entry into Oracle.
Volunteer checked in by the Divison.
Retain copies of any completed forms (and any attachments) for the period determined by Caltech data retention policies.
Volunteer assignments can be up to two years.  To exend a Volunteers assignment, you must submit updated document to Human Resources.
Note: It may not be appropriate to follow some of the steps for some Caltech volunteers.  If you have questions, please contact Human Resources for guidance.

Payment for services by volunteers is not allowed.  However, the Institute may reimburse Caltech volunteers for actual and reasonable expenses incurred in connection with their volunteer activities, following standard Caltech reimbursement guidelines.
47,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Cho, So-Hye Sabbatical 2020",Appointment_Process.docx,"APPOINTMENT PROCESS
INITIATING A POSTDOCTORAL SCHOLAR, VISITOR OR VISITING ASSOCIATE APPOINTMENT
Gather  the  following  information  from  the  candidate:
Note: Visitors staying at Caltech for 30 or fewer days require a guest or volunteer appointment. See “Guests and Volunteers” at http://www.cce.caltech.edu/staff-handbook

Visiting Associate: Often, a colleague of a Caltech professorial faculty member who is here to collaborate on research. He may be a professor on sabbatical from another university, a research scientist with an industry position, or  a JPL  employee conducting research with a Caltech faculty member. The person  must  have  a  permanent  faculty  position  or  its equivalent outside Caltech, to which she  will return  upon  completion of her Caltech appointment.

Postdoctoral  Scholar:  Postdoctoral  scholars  and  senior  postdoctoral  scholars  are  considered to be temporary interim employees. Postdocs and senior postdocs always work under close supervision of one or more Caltech professorial faculty members. Postdocs and senior postdocs are a separate group, distinct from faculty, staff, and students. Time served in the rank of postdoctoral scholar cannot exceed the maximum of six years.

Senior Postdoctoral Scholar: Postdoctoral scholars are generally promoted to  the  rank  of Senior Postdoctoral Scholar after three years. Time served in the ranks of postdoctoral scholar and senior postdoctoral scholar cannot exceed the maximum of nine years. Persons who have held a postdoctoral position at another institution may be appointed directly to the senior postdoctoral  scholar  rank.

Visitor: The rank of Visitor is for someone who does not have a faculty position (or its equivalent) at another institution, but does have  an  established  position  or relationship, such as  postdoctoral scholar, to  which  he will return  upon completion  of his Caltech  appointment. A visitor must be nominated by an active faculty member who is a colleague and is responsible for          making         his         or         her         stay         at         Caltech         mutually         beneficial.

RE: Berrow Foundation Lord Florey Scholarships

Michael Lerch is a gifted student with the potential to become a leading research scientist. He is a motivated and engaged experimentalist and I encourage you to give him your most careful consideration. Before working in my lab he already had significant research experience. He has performed research in an unusually broad diversity of scientific fields, with interests spanning from organometallic chemistry to cell biology. In combination with his studies at the ETHZ in interdisciplinary sciences, he has collected a vast knowledge of chemistry, biology and physics. He is thus uniquely positioned to tackle any challenge in the field of chemistry or biology. His remarkable training and his excellent scholar performances (grade average 5.41/6) have resulted in significant awards and honors in his young career, such as a scholarship from the Swiss Study Foundation and participation in an Erasmus LLP exchange at the University of Cambridge in the Laboratory of Prof. Ley.

Michael is currently conducting research in my laboratory in the context of his master thesis. Before his arrival here at Caltech, he showed an extraordinary interest in contributing intellectually to his project by providing creative input to the design of experiments. As a result of his initiative, Michael immediately became an important member of the research team upon his arrival. His efficiency in the lab, combined to his intelligence, have already led him to develop a new methodology for the preparation of important compounds of medicinal interest. The rapid progress he made in his project will likely lead to a first author manuscript as by the end of his thesis.

The project that he helped designed deals with the preparation of trifluoromethyl ketones using easily available allylic trifluoromethyl starting materials. In initial stages of the project, he successfully overcame a major synthetic challenge in the synthesis of the desired starting materials. He designed a new synthetic route to circumvent the initial problem encountered. His excellent knowledge of chemical databases combined with his ability to use spectroscopic methods significantly facilitated the rapid preparation of a wide variety of starting materials. The key aspect of his current research is the development of an efficient palladium-catalyzed oxidation of these substrates. His goal is the development of a regioselective access to trifluoromethylketones through palladium catalysis. He has already been able to successfully optimize the reaction conditions to provide high yields of the product on a test substrate. He will further extend the scope of starting materials amenable to this transformation. Beyond providing a streamlined access to important fluorinated products, his work will also further shine light on the effects determining the regioselectivity of the process. Overall, his dedicated and efficient work will greatly contribute to the nucleopalladation literature and guide further developments taking advantage of inductive effects.

Although he is already an effective researcher, I expect him to further improve in the context of his PhD studies. He has proved to be excellent at learning new concepts and new techniques, and he will likely succeed in overcoming any challenges he will encounter. Moreover, he is not afraid to ask questions and has proven to be an excellent and very interactive group member. He is thus not only scientifically gifted, but has proved to have the critical social abilities to become a successful leader in science.

I had the opportunity to talk with Michael numerous times about his ultimate career goals and what stands out the most from our discussions is his overwhelming enthusiasm for a variety of scientific disciplines. He is particularly excited to use the tools of chemistry, notably organic chemistry, to ultimately manipulate and interrogate biological systems. His uniquely diverse research experience positions him well to address the interdisciplinary challenges that are of the utmost importance to the scientific community. His excitement about sciences and his formidable work ethic makes me confident that whatever projects he embarks on throughout his career, his work is certain to have a positive impact on the scientific community. He has been an excellent group citizen in his short time in the group.  He always does more than his part in any task and he is very generous with his time in helping others.  I look forward to watching Michael continue to develop as a scientist. I recommend him highly and I am sure he will thrive in your stimulating environment as he embarks on the next chapter of his education.

column1: 51,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Wang JC Reapoint Sept 2020",Statement of JC.docx,"Overarching goal

The development of CO2 utilization technology has received tremendous research interest recently, because global CO2 emissions have doubled in the past three decades which results in climate change and has a profound effect on the environment. Electrochemical CO2 reduction reaction (CO2RR) provides a valuable approach in this area because electricity could ultimately come from renewable and clean sources of energy such as wind and solar. Although pure copper is active in producing multi-carbon products, the selective production of one or two products is challenging. Despite elegant breakthroughs in the past two decades, there is still an unmet need for a material that is active, selective, stable, and cost-effective in promoting CO2 electroreduction. An effective polymeric catalyst coating is highly desirable since only a relatively small amount of material is needed to cover the surface of the catalyst. Our goal is to utilize the polymer technology developed in the Grubbs group to enhance the selectivity, activity, and stability in an affordable manner, so that to pave the way for the future industrial application.
My achievement in the past year

column2: We envisioned that a random copolymer incorporating different functional groups might possess the modularity to tune the selectivity, conductivity and stability with high degree of freedom. During the past year, we have identified a family of copolymers that is effective for this purpose. Such a copolymer consists of three parts, which are expected to have an influence on the selectivity, conductivity and stability, respectively. The first part is called the “co-catalyst”, which contains reactive moiety to stabilize the desired transition state through supramolecular interactions. The second part is an ionomer which is designed for anion diffusion and conductivity. The third part is a “cross-linker” that could increase the stability of the copolymer and avoid delamination. Using a flow cell setup and 0.1 M KHCO3 as the electrolyte, the Faradic efficiencies for ethylene and ethanol production doubled (ethylene: from 22% to 55%, ethanol from 9% to 20%) whereas the undesired methane and hydrogen formation dropped to 2% and 10%, respectively.

First, we would like to complete our study on copolymer effect on the planar cooper plate. A clearer structure-activity relationship is expected to be achieved by conducting more control experiments. Besides, more characterization studies (e.g. SEM, XPS) would be conducted. Second, we would like to apply this technology to other catalytic systems. It is known that some copper nanostructure and bimetallic catalysts outperforms the simple copper plate catalyst. We envision that the interplay between copolymer and catalyst surface might further enhance the selectivity and/or stability. We are also curious about the support effect for our system as well as molecular catalysts confined in the polymer ion gel. Third, it is desirable to achieve high current density for practical utility. In this aspect, we would like to explore whether our system is compatible with the gas-diffusion electrode. The development of CO2 utilization technology has received tremendous research interest recently, because global CO2 emissions have doubled in the past three decades which results in climate change and has a profound effect on the environment. Electrochemical CO2 reduction reaction (CO2RR) provides a valuable approach in this area because electricity could ultimately come from renewable and clean sources of energy such as wind and solar. Although pure copper is active in producing multi-carbon products, the selective production of one or two products is challenging. Despite elegant breakthroughs in the past two decades, there is still an unmet need for a material that is active, selective, stable, and cost-effective in promoting CO2 electroreduction. An effective polymeric catalyst coating is highly desirable since only a relatively small amount of material is needed to cover the surface of the catalyst. Our goal is to utilize the polymer technology developed in the Grubbs group to enhance the selectivity, activity, and stability in an affordable manner, so that to pave the way for the future industrial application.

We envisioned that a random copolymer incorporating different functional groups might possess the modularity to tune the selectivity, conductivity and stability with high degree of freedom. During the past year, we have identified a family of copolymers that is effective for this purpose. Such a copolymer consists of three parts, which are expected to have an influence on the selectivity, conductivity and stability, respectively. The first part is called the “co-catalyst”, which contains reactive moiety to stabilize the desired transition state through supramolecular interactions. The second part is an ionomer which is designed for anion diffusion and conductivity. The third part is a “cross-linker” that could increase the stability of the copolymer and avoid delamination. Using a flow cell setup and 0.1 M KHCO3 as the electrolyte, the Faradic efficiencies for ethylene and ethanol production doubled (ethylene: from 22% to 55%, ethanol from 9% to 20%) whereas the undesired methane and hydrogen formation dropped to 2% and 10%, respectively.

First, we would like to complete our study on copolymer effect on the planar cooper plate. A clearer structure-activity relationship is expected to be achieved by conducting more control experiments. Besides, more characterization studies (e.g. SEM, XPS) would be conducted. Second, we would like to apply this technology to other catalytic systems. It is known that some copper nanostructure and bimetallic catalysts outperforms the simple copper plate catalyst. We envision that the interplay between copolymer and catalyst surface might further enhance the selectivity and/or stability. We are also curious about the support effect for our system as well as molecular catalysts confined in the polymer ion gel. Third, it is desirable to achieve high current density for practical utility. In this aspect, we would like to explore whether our system is compatible with the gas-diffusion electrode.

column2: I am pleased by your interest in my research group and wish to offer you a position in my group. As I understand the situation, you have funding from NSERC (National Sciences and Engineering Council of Canada) for the period of November 21, 2011 until August 22, 2013 and the initial appointment will be for that period.  Your salary will be $40,000 per annum.  It is anticipated that additional funding for several months after this period will be available as required for you future plans.

I look forward to meeting you at Caltech and discussing our collaboration.

column1: 56,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Yu (Yan) postdoc reapointment 2020",Statement of Yan Xu.docx,"Overarching goal

Internal olefins are important building blocks in modern drugs, agrochemicals, and functional materials, and are convenient handles for complex target syntheses. The configuration of internal olefins, commonly defined as E or Z, determine the overall configuration of the molecules, thereby influencing their physical, chemical, and biological properties. As an important technique to build internal olefins, olefin metathesis dominantly furnishes E olefins as the major product, while the selective construction of Z olefins remains rare. Previously, the Grubbs group has successfully developed two generations of Z-selective olefin metathesis catalysts, all featuring an additional Ru chelation and a bulky side chain of the NHC ligands. Though effective, their wide-spread application is still limited by (1) unsatisfying catalyst turnover number and (2) poor tolerance to electrophilic functional groups. My overarching goal is to further advance the Z-selective metathesis technique through the design and development of novel catalysts.
My achievement in the past year

In the past year, I was able to develop a so-called “third-generation” Z-selective catalyst, which was inaccessible previously. The key breakthrough came from the utilization of an “acid-base quenching” strategy, which, for the first time, provided sufficient driving force for the construction of an extremely sterically demanding ruthenium di-pivalate as the key intermediate towards the catalyst synthesis. This new catalyst has already demonstrated unprecedented reactivity and functional group tolerance according to our preliminary tests, which leads to efficient syntheses towards previously hard-to-access chemical structures.

For example, ubiquitously found in bioactive compounds and synthetic building blocks, (Z)-α,β-unsaturated amides are commonly assembled through partial hydrogenation of ynonamides or Wittig-type reactions, and more recently stereoretentive metathesis of (Z)-but-2-enamides. While effective, these processes all require expansive, advanced starting materials that are less convenient to access especially on a large scale. Featuring the use of feedstock acrylamides and terminal olefins, an appealing alternative can be envisioned through Z-selective metathesis. However, as C–H chelated ruthenium catalysts are reportedly less compatible with electrophilic substrates, such a process remains elusive with no known example. Enabled by the successful development of the “third-generation” catalyst, efficient Z-selective olefin-acrylamide cross-metathesis is realized for the first time.

column2: First, we would like to complete our study in Z-selective olefin-acrylamide cross-metathesis. We are also collaborating with a computational group to depict a clearer structure-activity relationship. Second, we would like to apply this technique to other reaction types, such as the Z-selective cross-metathesis with regular olefins. We envision that an ultra-high turnover number might be achievable. If so, we might further transfer the technique into the production of important agriculture chemicals, such as insect pheromones. Third, we are curious about whether the Z-selective catalyst could be further advanced. In this aspect, we would like to explore the installation of a type of side-chains that are even bulkier than the current “third-generation” catalyst.",3441,"[-3.86201382e-01  3.70994419e-01  6.54148877e-01 -1.95636153e-01

61,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Siu Fong Lee 2014/Siu-Fung Lee student 2014 submitted",Brief_Description_of_Research_Project(part_IV).docx,"In our work, we will prepare a polymeric core/shell hybrids inorganic nanoparticle, or called “breathing” nanoparticle, as a novel drug carrier.  This nanoparticle is composed by designed polymer for core and an iron oxide porous shell.  In this system, polymeric core can undergo swelling or unswelling process under specific conditions, such as change in pH and temperature, while the iron oxide porous shell can provide a protective layer to enhance polymeric stability towards the surrounding and also serves as MR contrasting imaging agent.

In our study, the polymer will be unswelled for cargo loading by heat induction with the alternating magnetic field. In this process, the polymeric core will undergo changing of conformation, such that the solvent trapped by the polymeric core can be removed.  Noticeably, the polymeric core will be shrinked in this process and provide an external force to pull the cargo into the nanoparticles.   In opposite, the cargo can be released during the swelling process by applying external stimuli, such that the polymeric core will be expanded and provide an additional force to push the cargo into the surrounding.  This “breathing” behavior can significant enhance the release percentage of hollow-type nanoparticles in drug delivery system.  Also, this nano-carrier can act as a nanoreactor, in which the reactant can be artificially transported across the nanoreactor, instead of simple diffusion.

In our study, polymeric core is the key of the artificial motion of the cargo across the nanosystem. As we know that, Prof. Robert H Grubbs is a Nobel laureate, and is a very famous organic chemist. His research group focuses on the design and synthesis of organometallic catalysts and for use in organic and polymer synthesis.  In our work, it is essential to prepare a novel and tunable polymeric nanoparticles, in which the structure, as well as their nano-architecture (including its size, morphology, and surface functionalization), and the properties (such as swelling) of the polymeric nanoparticles must be well controlled.  In order to solve this technical problems, different type of ruthenium based metathesis catalysts designed by Prof. Grubbs, should be used , which can be easily capable in Prof. Grubbs Laboratory.  Also, his group already successfully prepares highly functionalized polymers with controlled structures by the ruthenium based metathesis catalysts.  With their research experience in polymer science and our technique in nanotechnology, it will be a promising collaborative project and benefit both our research team.

Moreover, the facilities in California Institute of Technology (including electron microscopy, polymer synthesis and mass spectrometry) can provide a good and more accessible platform for me to characterize this novel polymeric hybrid inorganic nanoparticle (including its swelling properties and its nano-architecture), as well as other research projects carried in my Ph.D study.  Also, visiting in California Institute of Technology can provide a good opportunity for me to learn more in polymer science and other aspects with other famous chemist.",3146,"[-2.09320188e-01  4.50403929e-01  5.49141347e-01 -1.50903776e-01
62,"desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/RHG Group/RHG Misc Postdoc""Visitors/Siu Fong Lee 2014/Siu-Fung Lee student 2014 submitted",letter_of_invitation.docx,"March 5, 2013
The Chinese University of Hong Kong
I am pleased to invite you to visit and be a Ph.D. exchange student in my laboratory in the Division of Chemistry and Chemical Engineering at California Institute of Technology, USA for a few months.

As proposed, you will collaborate closely with my student on research related to polymeric core/shell inorganic nanoparticles and its applications towards drug delivery.  During the visiting period, we will be able to provide you with office/laboratory space, chemical and instrument needed for your research work. Additionally, I expect that you will be involved in many activities that will allow for cultural exchange and research discussion among our students.
We look forward to your time here at California Institute of Technology, USA. I believe our collaboration and this opportunity for exchange will allow us to learn much from each other.

column2: Recently, a joint effort by the Grubbs and Atwater groups at CalTech has enabled the synthesis of brush block copolymers (BCPs) BCPs that self-assemble into lamellar arrays with periodicities on the order of 10s to 100s of nanometers. These polymers consist of a polynorbornene polymer as a backbone, with large, polymeric brushes protruding off of the central polymer core. Interestingly, due to the steric bulk of the polymer brushes, these materials rapidly assembly into 1-D photonic crystals upon drying, reflecting light at wavelengths that are tunable within the UV-Vis and IR regions of the electromagnetic spectrum by varying the molecular weight of the BCPs. These materials are promising for a diverse set of applications wherein one would want to manipulate and control light in the UV, visible, and IR regions of the spectrum, such as reflective coatings or laser cavities. However, significant challenges remain in both understanding and manipulating the fundamental interactions so as to create a more diverse, controllable array of nanoscale morphologies, to understand the assembly processes that generate the PCs, and to fabricate useful structures that can be used for the aforementioned applications. To fully address these challenges, a multi-disciplinary approach is necessary, requiring expertise in polymer synthesis, self-assembly, materials characterization, and computational modeling of material properties.

Herein, this proposal outlines key goals for the development of BCP based PCs, as well as several strategies to achieve these goals. Importantly, these strategies require the polymer synthesis expertise of the Grubbs group and the materials characterization and modeling capabilities of the Atwater group.  The key areas of expertise that I will bring to this project are an understanding of self-assembly processes in nanoscale-sized materials, as well as experience with the characterization methods necessary to both determine material structure and understand the fundamental assembly processes.

column1: Goal 1: Improve long-range ordering of BCP assemblies using templated synthesis techniques

column2: High quality PCs with tunable band gaps require nanometer-scale features with significant long-range ordering. Although the previously generated lamellar structures have indeed exhibited photonic band gaps, no significant long-range order has been observed, especially for BCPs with molecular weights greater than 5000 kDa. This makes control over the band gap challenging, especially for materials that manipulate light in the IR region of the spectrum. To address this challenge, I will use templated synthesis techniques to align the BCP structures during the assembly process (Fig. 1). The first target templates that will be used to direct the alignment of BCPs during the assembly process are vapor-liquid-solid (VLS) generated silicon wire arrays that have been synthesized in the Atwater laboratory. The VLS arrays constitute vertical pillars that are positioned in arbitrarily determined locations across a substrate. The chemical synthesis expertise of the Grubbs group should aid in the development of strategies to coat the VLS arrays with molecules that preferentially interact with the chemical functionalities on only one of the blocks of the BCP, thus driving the BCP structures to wrap around the pillars in a predetermined manner. Control over spacing and arrangement of these pillars relative to one another should enable control over the orientation and lamellar spacing of the assembled BCP structures. The initial targeted structures will constitute square and rectangular arrays, as these are predicted to be compatible with the previously developed lamellar ordered structures. Modeling of the properties of these materials, taking into consideration the effects that the silicon pillars may have on the way these materials interact with light, with be performed using methods that have been developed in the Atwater group.

column1: Goal 2: Generate self-assembled structures with diverse morphologies

column2: For many of the aforementioned applications of PCs, 2-D or 3-D ordered materials would provide a significant advantage over the previously generated 1-D lamellar arrays, as the PC band gap would be observed when irradiated with light from a larger range of angles (lamellar structures only exhibit a band gap when irradiated perpendicular to their lamellar ordering). The BCP architectures generated by the Grubbs group have many different chemical handles that can be used to control how different blocks interact with one another. The thermodynamically favored morphology of the assembled structure will always be the one that maximizes favorable chemical interactions between BCPs, while simultaneously minimizing unfavorable chemical and steric interactions. Thus, controlling each of these forces during the assembly process by changing the size and shape, as well as the chemical functional groups present on the BCP will enable the synthesis of a more diverse set of ordered structures.

column1: All of the lamellar structures generated to date involve the synthesis of BCPs with blocks that are equal in size, and express brush structures of the same length. By changing the size ratio of each of the polymer blocks, it should be possible to drive the formation of different morphologies that are formed (Fig. 2A). It is also a simple matter to change the length of each of the brushes on each of the polymer blocks—this would mean that the shape of the BCP would transition from rod-like to cone-like in shape (Fig. 2B). Each of these morphological changes have been demonstrated to generate 2-D hexagonal ordering and 3-D body-centered cubic ordering in other polymeric structures, dependent upon the relative cone- or rod-like character of the polymer. These two structural variations can also be performed simultaneously in a combinatorial-like approach to create a library of structures that can be screened for different morphologies and physical properties. From this set of targets, it should be possible to extrapolate trends and determine the fundamental relationship between BCP structure and the resulting self-assembled morphology.

More intricate self-assembled morphologies will also be generated by synthesizing materials with more complex BCP structures, including tri-block copolymers that contain three discrete phase-segregating sections, or block copolymers that contain both rigid brush and more flexible non-brush sections. Each of these materials will have different sets of chemical interactions and steric constraints that would change the molecular interactions that drive the assembly process. IPolymeric brush structures that contain hydrogen bonding or salt-bridging groups (such as carboxylic acids, amines, guanidinium moieties, or other functional groups) that can introduce hydrogen bonding and electrostatic interactions will also be investigated as means to direct specific chemical interactions between BCPs during the assembly process.
Goal 3: Establish computational model systems that predict ideal structures to tune BCP and PC physical properties

column2: Because there are many different ways in which the BCP structures can be modified (vide supra), it will be important to approach the synthesis of new nanostructured materials both by exploring different synthetic routes to determine which  morphologies are accessible, and also by using computational techniques to specifically identify target architectures that possess ideal photonic properties. Importantly, simulations of material properties can be done jointly with the aforementioned synthetic advancements, and the two types of experiments should inform one another as the research progresses. Key target architectures already include 2-D hexagonal and 3-D body-centered cubic morphologies, but there exists a rich array of potential architectures that can be synthesized; it will be important to use computational techniques to determine which of these structures are ideal for the application of generating photonic crystals with band gaps at a specific wavelength, or other types of materials for which these structures may present use. These models will also provide a beneficial characterization tool, as the modeled properties can be used to confirm the identities of the structures that are synthesized. Techniques such as SEM can be used to investigate structure in the lamellar arrays, but probing the structures of the 2-D or 3-D ordered materials will be more complicated. Developing computational techniques that correlate physical structure with photonic properties will allow for further confirmation of material structure.

column1: Goal 4: Develop methods to generate structures with larger periodicities

As mentioned previously, the PC band gaps in these materials are dependent upon the length scale of the structure’s periodicity, with larger periods giving rise to band gaps at longer wavelengths. This presents a challenge for developing band gaps in the IR, as it necessitates structures with very large periodicities, which are difficult to assemble, as mentioned in goal 1. Synthesizing materials on this length scale is challenging due to the fact that larger BCPs are typically more polydisperse, and thus the ordering of the assembled structure is typically not as high. However, it is also possible to tune the band gap by changing the difference between the refractive indeces of the different blocks of the BCP, specifically by incorporating different atomic or molecular species within the BCP. For example, materials that bind metal ions (such as charged species like carboxylic acids, or materials with high binding affinity for metal ions like crown ethers) will be incorporated either along the brushes of the polymer, or at the tips of the brushes, thereby localizing inorganic materials as specific points in the assembled structure. These types of binding interactions may also be used to change the morphology of the assembled structure (as mentioned in goal 2). Structures that sequester metal ions may also be useful in nucleating solid metal species, such as noble metal nanoparticles, within different regions of the assembled structure; this would be predicted to provide a significant change in the refractive index, as well as generate new types of optical phenomena like plasmon resonances. It is unknown how these materials would behave under UV-Vis-IR light irradiation, so the expertise of the Atwater group in modeling material properties would be crucial for predicting emergent optical phenomena. It should also be possible to introduce chemical functionalities across the BCP structure to cross-link and/or cleave different portions of the materials post-assembly. I.E. a structure can be synthesized such that the brushes on one block can be cross-linked and covalently connected, while the brushes on the other block can be cleaved from the polymer backbone. After such a structure is assembled, the cross-linking and cleaving steps can be performed to first stabilize the assembled structure and subsequently remove one of the polymer components. This would generate a structure with alternating regions of solid polymer and empty space; the refractive index of air is significantly different from any polymer species that would be utilized, thereby maximizing the differences in refractive index within a structure. A combination of these strategies, along with those outlined in goals 2 and 3, should allow for the design of materials that place PC band gaps across the UV, visibile, and IR regions of the electromagnetic spectrum without necessitating the synthesis of large BCPs or structures with large periodicities.

In summary, I propose a series of strategies for synthesizing PCs based upon brush BCPs. This research requires a joint effort between the Atwater and Grubbs groups, as each has special expertise in the areas of materials characterization and modeling, and materials synthesis, respectively. Combined with my own expertise in self-assembly and materials characterization, we should be able to synthesize a diverse array of nanostructured architectures that herald a new type of material for use in the manipulation of light. Such materials may find application in energy related goals such as solar reflection or solar energy harvesting, and would also have a significant impact on the scientific community in both understanding fundamental assembly properties at the nanoscale, and fundamental light-matter interactions.
I am writing this letter to explain why I have to leave Carnegie Mellon before I give my Ph.D. thesis defense in January 2012.

I am a 4th year graduate student at Carnegie Mellon University, working toward my Ph.D. degree in Chemistry with Prof. Newell Washburn. I was looking for a postdoctoral position starting in January 2012 soon after my possible thesis defense date. While I was seeking a postdoctoral position, I had a chance to contact Prof. Grubbs at Cal Tech and we agreed on working together. Because Prof. Grubbs needs me as soon as possible for his urgent research progress, my current advisor, Prof. Grubbs and I discussed about my appropriate thesis defense date. The best time for my Ph.D. thesis defense would be in January 2012 because I need to complete a few publications and experiments from Prof. Washburn’s lab until the time that I leave for Cal Tech. Also I will finish my thesis writing by the time of my Ph.D. thesis defense date using after-hours and weekends.

In conclusion, if I start working in Prof. Grubbs lab in August 2011 prior to my thesis defense on January 2012, then Prof. Washburn, Prof. Grubbs and I would all be satisfied without detriment to either group’s research.

column2: My Postdoctoral position in the Grubbs group will last 3 months, at most, and serve to conclude important work from my Ph.D. studies. Following recent successes with data acquisition and process development, which were quite elusive during my Ph.D. studies, we believe we now have sufficient data to write and submit multiple manuscripts to high-impact journals. We have 1-2 weeks of experimental work remaining in order to get all necessary data to this end. Writing these manuscripts will be tasked to me, as I've been working on this project for over 5 years now.

In addition to research and writing, my other primary objective as a Postdoctoral Scholar in the Grubbs Group will be to mentor and train a first year student, Quan Gan. He will be taking over my work when I leave, as well as assuming my managerial and administrative roles within the group. It is crucial both for the group as a whole, and for Quan specifically, that he becomes fully trained in order to maximize his success and efficiency during his time as a Ph.D. student at Caltech.",1075,"[-5.87227345e-01  4.24265742e-01  4.28904593e-01 -1.47496641e-01

Support information is required for each key personnel/PI. All financial resources (Federal, non-Federal, commercial, or institutional) should be included.
A separate entry should be included for each grant, FWP, or other source of support for the PI.

column2: Personal Statement

column1: Dougherty applies the concepts and techniques of physical organic chemistry to the complex neuroreceptors and ion channels of the nervous system. Using the tools of chemistry, molecular biology, and electrophysiology he has provided high precision insights into the interactions of drubs with neuroreceptors and the mechanisms by which proteins of the synapse communicate information throughout the central and peripheral nervous systems. His expertise in physical organic chemistry lead to his discovery of the cation-pi interaction, a universally employed noncovalent binding interaction that contributes to protein structure and to drug-receptor interactions. In addition, his earlier work on organic molecules with novel optical, electrical, and photochemical properties has allowed him to design novel photochemical probes of ion channel and neuroreceptor function.

89,desktop_grubbs_assistant/2 RHG/Grants/USC Keck Aug 2015 copy/Ready for Keck,DAD SOW.docx,"Statement of Work
During the last granting period we probed three new photochemical processes that have the potential to produce long wavelength photodecaging. These are:

Photoreduction-trimethyl lock chemistry: we have invented a new photochemical reaction; shown that it can release GABA and activate neuroreceptors expressed in a vertebrate cell; evaluated the mechanism of this new reaction; and designed and synthesized next generation compounds that will have the desired optical and biological properties.

Methylene blue photochemistry: we have invented a new photochemical reaction based on the well-known, WHO essential medicine methylene blue; used the new reaction to decage compounds at >700 nm; and designed and synthesized next generation compounds that will have the desired optical and biological properties.
Photoacids: we have probed the structural constraints and are nearly finished the synthesis of a compound that absorbs at >800 nm and has a built-in quinomethide unit for photoacid induced decaging.
During the next granting period we will focus on:

Optimizing the photoreduction-trimethyl lock chemistry. We are very close to having compounds that absorb in the appropriate wavelength range and perform efficient chemistry. Note that the insights we have gained from our mechanistic chemistry were crucial in designing efficient photodecaging routes.

Developing the methylene blue chemistry. We are already very near the optimal wavelength region. We need to refine the photochemistry and develop a better understanding of the optimal decaging strategies.
Choosing the best drugs for decaging.
Testing the toxicity of all compounds, both photochemical precursors and also photochemical products.
Evaluating the blood-brain barrier penetration properties of optimal compounds.

Developing an efficient method for the synthesis of UCNPs on a moderate scale.
Work on reproducibility of synthesis of basic particles.
Explore methods for the scale up of particles.
Designing new synthetic methods for the caging of drug molecules on the UCNPs.
Develop new photolabile linking chemistry for efficient release.
Develop methods for the functionalization of carrier polymers before attachment to UCNPs.
Develop coupling chemistry for PEGs to render particles biocompatible.
Developing pulse sequences for the most efficient un-caging of drugs from UCNPs.
Demonstrating that sufficient light can penetrate the skull for the release of drugs from CNPs in an animal model.
Use appropriate animal models as developed at USC

column2: Personal Statement

column1: Our laboratory at Caltech is involved in a broad range of projects in organic materials science. Although our laboratory has been involved in the development of new methods for the synthesis of large and small molecules, over the past several years we are turning more to the design and synthesis of materials for medical applications.  A number of these projects involved the use of radiation to modify materials inside the body.  For example, we have aided in the design of materials for the manufacture of intraocular lens that can be modified by light after implantation.  The present project requires the release of pharmaceutical agents using long wavelength light.  We are designing up converting nanoparticles to accomplish this goal.

We have a late start in the project.  We have had some difficulty in hiring a postdoctoral fellow for the project.  Initially an offer was made to Dr. Delian Yang (Ph. D. Colorado State University) who was to start on October 1, 2014.  However, he accepted an industrial job just two weeks before he was to start.  Then we went through the process of advertising the position and received quite a few applications.  After consulting with Dr. Nayef Alsaifi, we decided to make an offer to Dr. Pengfei Zhang, who received his Ph. D. in Physics from Naikai University and was a postdoctoral fellow with Prof. Jianzhong Wu at University of California, Riverside, one of the world’s leading expert on statistical mechanical density functional theory.  There paperwork took some time, but he has just moved to Pasadena and will start April 1.
During the visit to KFUPM, I had extensive discussions with Dr. Nayef Alsaifi, and we outlined a detailed research plan, which includes the following four projects:
Microscopic theory for salts effects on miscibility of binary liquid mixtures.
Density functional theory for the phase behavior and interfacial properties in polyelectrolyte blends.
Experimental and theoretical Interfacial tension in Squalane-CO2 systems.
Bifurcations and stability analysis of multiple densities from PC-SAFT EOS: multiple density roots.

Dr. Alsaifi has already made progress on Project 4 working with a Masters student.  He will also conduct experiments to measure the interfacial tension in Squalane-CO2 systems.  The new postdoc will be working on Projects 1 and 2, with close participation by Dr. Alsaifi.
