column2: The production of polyolefins via coordination-insertion polymerization by metal catalysts is an enormous industry, ca. 9 million tons of which was based on the use of single-site catalysis in 20091. The use of homogeneous, single-site catalysts has allowed development of catalysts for tacticity control in the polymerization of α-olefins2, polar monomer copolymerization to functional polyolefins3, and, more recently, the combination of stereocontrol with tolerance for polar monomers4. Most of these systems feature isolated metal sites, however, the development of polymerization catalysts featuring multiple active sites in close proximity is of great interest for their potential to exhibit, in comparison with related monometallic catalysts, higher degrees of functional group tolerance, tacticity control, activity, and selectivity.

Pioneering work by the Marks group on the synthesis of and polymerization by homobimetallic Zr5 and Ti complexes and heterobimetallic Ti-Cr complexes6 has established their utility as active catalysts for the polymerization of ethylene to linear and highly branched polymers respectively. Dizirconium phenoxy-imine complexes A (Figure 1) catalyze the homopolymerization of ethylene with an 8-fold increase in activity versus related monometallic complexes5a. The bimetallic complexes are also competent for ethylene-1-hexene copolymerization with up to 11 % comonomer incorporation, while the monometallic complex is inactive even for ethylene homopolymerization under similar conditions. Heterobimetallic Ti-Cr complexes (B, Figure 1) can also be prepared for tandem ethylene polymerization/oligomerization at the two metal sites respectively, resulting in synthesis of highly-branched ethylene-co-1-hexene polymers from a single ethylene feed6a, 6b. This system results in polymers with up to 26 branches per 1000 C, while reactions performed with un-tethered Ti and Cr result in polymers with only 6 branches per 1000 C. Cooperative activation of substrates through concurrent agostic interaction and olefin coordination has been proposed for both of these systems.

column1: Figure 1. Homobimetallic Zr and heterobimetallic Ti-Cr complexes for the synthesis of  ethylene-α-olefin copolymers via direct copolymerization and tandem polymerization/oligomerization catalysis.

column2: More recent work by the Osakada group on the synthesis of bimetallic Ni7, Pd8, and Fe9 complexes supported by rigid macrocyclic binucleating ligands (Figure 2) has demonstrated the utility of these complexes towards improved ethylene polymerization activity and the incorporation of functional olefins. Dinickel complexes C are competent for the copolymerization of ethylene with unsaturated dienes and with unsaturated long-chain esters resulting in copolymers with 3.6 % incorporation of 1,6-heptadiene and 1.4 % tert-butyl butenoate7. Their related monometallic complex produces only trace polymer in the presence of functional monomers and no copolymer in the presence of even 1,5-hexadiene. Dinuclear α-diimine complex D is active for ethylene-methyl acrylate copolymerization to highly-branched copolymers8. Up to 85 % of the incorporation occurs in the middle of a branch; copolymerizations by mononuclear complexes result in only 21 % incorporation at these positions with the remaining 79 % incorporations at chain ends. This macrocyclic ligand design has most recently been applied to the preparation of diiron and dicobalt bis(imino)pyridine complexes E9. At temperatures between 80 to 100 oC the Fe complexes produce linear polyethylene with small distributions in molecular weight (PDI = 1.75 – 2.77) and good activities (up to 975 g mmolFe-1 h-1 atm-1 at 100 oC). Both bimetallic Co and Fe complexes can polymerization ethylene at 1 atm with up to a 15.5-fold increase in Mn versus the monometallic system.

column1: Figure 2. Bimetallic systems prepared by the Osakada group for ethylene and functional monomer copolymerization (C and D) and for enhanced ethylene polymerization stability (E).

column2: In designing new bimetallic polymerization systems, consideration of the degree to which changes in reactivity of bimetallic catalysts arise from the interactions of the two metal centers guides design of the binucleating ligand framework. While numerous examples have been reported of molecules featuring two potentially active sites, as shown above, many of these examples lack precise placement of the two sites in close proximity due to the flexibility of the linker. Use of a rigid para or meta terphenyl backbone (F and G in Figure 3) decorated with functional groups to support either early or late metals allows for synthesis of bimetallic complexes with fixed metal-metal geometries. The central terphenyl arene may also be substituted, resulting in hindered C-C bond rotation about the central arene and isolation of either syn or anti atropisomers of the complexes. In the syn atropisomers effects from the interactions of the two metal centers and their coordination spheres would be expected to be observed. Effects observed for the anti atropisomers result from placement of the two sites on a single ligand framework. The sterics of the terphenyl linker will influence polymerization by both atropisomers of the bimetallic catalysts, so to probe the effects of the central arene, polymerizations by control monometallic complexes bearing a similar permethylated arene (H, Figure 3) should also be performed. The preparation of additional monometallic control complexes bearing simpler substitution may be needed to allow comparisons between bimetallic catalysts and those previously reported in the literature.

column1: Figure 3. Binucleating ligands based on the para terphenyl (F) and meta terphenyl (G) framework can feature a variety of donors to support either early or late bimetallic complexes with a fixed metal-metal geometry and distance. Mononucleating ligands H may also be prepared as control for the effects of the central arene on polymerization by bimetallic catalysts.

column2: The Agapie group first reported the synthesis of both syn and anti atropisomers of a dinickel phenoxy-iminato complex for enhanced amine tolerance10, α-olefin copolymerization11, and amino olefin incorporation12. Phenoxy-iminato Ni complexes were first reported by Grubbs, et al. in 1998 for ethylene homopolymerization13 and ethylene-norbornene copolymerization14. While the original complexes exhibit some tolerance for water, esters, alcohols, and ethers, they show substantial deactivation in the presence of tertiary amines14. In contrast, bimetallic complex I (Figure 4) is tolerant of tertiary, secondary, and primary amines during ethylene homopolymerization10. Copolymerization of ethylene and amino olefins can be accomplished by syn and anti atropisomers of complexes I and J to achieve comonomer incorporations of 0.1 – 1.3 %12. As the level of comonomer incorporation is independent of the distance between the olefin and functional group and the syn atropisomers retain a greater degree of their original activity this suggests that enchainment of these monomers does not require coordination of the amine at one metal center with enchainment of its olefin at the second metal center. Instead, it is proposed that the steric bulk of an N-coordinated complex on the bimetallic framework leads to coordination of the less sterically-demanding olefin at the second metal center in the syn atropisomers (Figure 4), leading to retention of activity and comonomer incorporation.

column1: Figure 4. Proposed mechanism for amino olefin incorporation by dinickel phenoxy-iminato catalysts supported by the para terphenyl (I) and meta terphenyl (J) framework. Figure adapted from reference 12.

column2: More recently a series of dizirconium complexes supported by a binucleating amine bisphenolate ligand was reported for enhanced tacticity control in the polymerization of propylene and 1-hexene15. Monometallic CS symmetric amine bisphenolate zirconium complexes were originally reported by Kol, et al. as highly active catalysts for the polymerization of 1-hexene to atactic poly-1-hexene16. Bimetallic complexes (LR4-L)Zr2 (Figure 5) supported by the para terphenyl backbone show greatly enhanced tacticity control, producing poly-1-hexene with up to 79 % mmmm. This is in contrast to the control monometallic complexes (LArCl2-L)Zr (Figure 5) which produce poly-1-hexene with up to 35 % mmmm and with greatly diminished activity. Tacticity control in this bimetallic system is proposed to result from the interactions of the growing polymeryl chain with the sterics of the distal metal site (Figure 6). As a result of the steric demand of the central coordination sites, the bulky polymer chain is proposed to favor coordination away from site and away from the bulk of the central arene. The interaction of the incoming monomer with the polymer results in selective insertion and the observed isotacticity.

column1: Figure 5. Bimetallic zirconium complexes supported by the para-terphenyl linker and monometallic control complexes bearing an analogous bulky arene substituent without the second metal site.
Figure 6. Proposed mechanism for tacticity control in dizirconium amine bisphenolate complexes. P = growing polymer chain. Figure adapted from reference 15.

column2: Initial studies of this dizirconium system allowed the development of the (LCl4-NMe2)Zr2 complex which shows significant improvement in activity and tacticity control, however, exploration of bimetallic complexes featuring large ortho substituents was not extensive and the effects of the metal-metal geometry on tacticity control was not explored. To address these gaps, the synthesis and characterization of bimetallic Zr complexes supported by a meta-terphenyl linker, (mLCl4-NMe2)Zr2, is presented. Preparation of para-terphenyl complexes bearing very bulky ortho-trialkysilyl and triarylsilyl substituents and their 1-hexene, propylene, and ethylene polymerization catalysis is also presented in addition to results from related monometallic complexes.

column1: Synthesis, Characterization by meta-Terphenyl-Derived Zirconium Polymerization Catalysts

Another way of probing the influence of the distal metal site on the tacticity of the resulting polymer is through modification of the geometry of the terphenyl linker. Moving from a para-terphenyl to meta-terphenyl framework would be expected to position the coordination spheres of the two metal sites closer to one another, which might lead to greater stereoselectivity.

column2: Negishi coupling of 1 with aryl dibromide 2 affords terphenyl 3 which may be doubly-lithiated and quenched with N,N-dimethylformamide and deprotected to afford 4 (Scheme 1). Two-step reductive amination of 4 with either N,N-dimethylethylenediamine or 2-methoxyethylamine leads to formation of secondary amines 5-L (L = OMe, NMe2). Reaction with benzyl bromide 6 affords proligands (mLCl4-OMe)H4 and (mLCl4-NMe2)H4. Reaction of these proligands with two equivalents of zirconium tetrabenzyl affords a mixture of three metalation isomers: one C1 symmetric species and two CS symmetric species.

column1: Scheme 1. Meta-terphenyl derived proligands were prepared by reductive amination of aldehyde 4 and subsequent condensation with benzyl bromide 6. These proligands may be metallated via protonolysis of ZrBn4, giving rise to three metalation isomers: two pseudo-CS isomers and one C1 isomer.

column2: The symmetry of the metalation isomers could be established using 1H NMR spectroscopy (Figure 7). Para-terphenyl-derived bimetallic zirconium complexes display two characteristic benzylic doublets downfield of 3 ppm; with the C1 symmetric isomers, the number of signals in this region is expected to increase to four as the two Zr centers are no longer symmetry related. The two CS symmetric isomers should each give rise to a set of two doublets in this region as the two Zr centers in each isomers are still symmetry related. Two species from the metallation of (mLCl4-NMe2)H4 can be isolated that display these NMR features (spectra 2 and 3 in Figure 7 corresponding to the C1 and CS symmetric isomers).

column1: Figure 7. 1H NMR of C2 symmetric para-terphenyl supported bimetallic zirconium complex and analogous C1 and CS symmetric meta-terphenyl supported dizirconium complexes.

The CS symmetric species (mLCl4-NMe2)Zr2 in spectrum 3 may be crystallographically characterized (Figure 8). While the data was only sufficient to determine connectivity, this confirms the identity of the Zr complex as the CS symmetric isomer with the two NMe2 moieties positioned towards one another. The Zr-Zr distance in this complex is 8.03 Ǻ, elongated from 7.62 Ǻ in the (LCl4-NMe2)Zr215 complex through rotation of the outer phenolates of the meta-terphenyl backbone. In comparison with the other structurally-characterized CS symmetric bimetallic complex, (LMe4-OMe)Zr2, the distance between the two L groups is greatly shorted from an O-O distance of 7.65 Ǻ in the para-terphenyl complex to an N-N distance of 5.81 Ǻ in the meta-terphenyl complex.
Figure 8. Solid-state structure of (mLCl4-NMe2)Zr2. Disordered pentane and H-atoms omitted for clarity.

column2: Work on the synthesis and characterization of meta-terphenyl-derived complexes featuring other substituents is ongoing. Isolation of individual metalation isomers of (mLCl4-OMe)Zr2 has not yet been successful. Furthermore, methods for clean isolation of single metalation isomers of (mLCl4-NMe2)Zr2 have not been fully developed. Examination of the activity and stereoselectivity of these systems, through 1-hexene and propylene polymerization experiments, will be performed once the complexes have been cleanly isolated.

column1: Synthesis and Characterization of and Polymerization by Ortho-Silyl Substituted Zirconium Complexes

column2: Trialkylsilyl substituents may be facilely introduced ortho to a phenol via use of the retro-Brook rearrangement developed by Rawal, et al. for the synthesis of silyl-substituted salen ligands17. Silylation of 2,6-dibromo-4-tert-butylphenol (10) with imidazole affords a silyl ether (11) that may be doubly-lithiated using tert-butyllithium. Upon warming this species undergoes a retro-Brook rearrangement and the remaining aryllithium may be quenched N,N-dimethylformamide to afford aldehyde 12R. Sequential reductive amination of 12R with the desired primary amine, either N,N-dimethylethylenediamine or 2-methoxyethylamine, affords secondary amine 13R-L (R = iPr, Ph; L = OMe, NMe2).

column1: Scheme 2. Preparation of ortho-silyl-substituted aldehydes via silyl ether formation and subsequent retro-Brook rearrangement upon ortho-lithiation. Aldehydes 12R may be reductively aminated with the desired primary amine to afford secondary amines 13R-L as precursors for mono- and binucleating proligands.

Binucleating proligands (LSiR3-L)H4 (R = iPr, L = NMe2; R = iPr, L = OMe; R = Ph, L = NMe2) were synthesized as shown in Scheme 3. These proligands may be metallated via reaction of two equivalents of ZrBn4 with the desired binucleating proligand. 1H NMR analysis of the crude reaction mixtures indicates that this this reaction results in the formation of two metalation isomers. These two species are assigned to a C2 and CS symmetric isomer where the two L donors are on opposite sides or the same side of the central arene respectively. The C2 symmetric isomer of (LSiiPr3-NMe2)Zr2 could be structurally characterized by single-crystal X-ray diffraction studies and its structure is shown in Figure 9.

As activity and tacticity effects observed for the bimetallic catalysts can result from either the distal steric effect of the second metal on the selectivity or from steric bulk of the central arene linker, it is imperative to also examine monometallic complexes bearing the analogous permethylated arene. The mononucleating proligand bearing an ortho pentamethylarene substituent and a triisopropyl silyl substituent was synthesized through reaction of the corresponding secondary amine 13iPr-NMe2 with benzyl bromide 22 (Scheme 4). Metallation was also accomplished by reaction with one equivalent of ZrBn4.

Scheme 4. Preparation of monometallic Zr complexes bearing ortho-pentamethylarene substitution as controls for the effect of the central arene on polymerization by para-terphenyl supported bimetallic zirconium complexes.

Catalysis of ethylene and 1-hexene polymerization by (LSiiPr3-NMe2)Zr2 and its monometallic control complex was examined and the results are summarized in Tables 1 and 2. Both bimetallic and monometallic Zr complexes supported by the SiiPr3 ligands with NMe2 donors were found to have decomposed upon handling and storage, so the reported activities and tacticities may reflect contributions from the decomposition products. Work is underway to understand the nature of these decomposition products and to repeat polymerization trials with authentic samples of the dibenzyl zirconium complexes. Based on the initial polymerization data, however, the bimetallic complex exhibits a higher activity for 1-hexene polymerization with MAO activators (0.98 kg mmolZr-1 h-1 versus 0.14 kg mmolZr-1 h-1 for the monometallic complex), albeit with less tacticity control (17 % mmmm for the bimetallic versus 34 % mmmm for the monometallic). When activated by [HNMe2Ph][B(C6F5)4] the bimetallic complex shows an ~10-fold increase in activity compared with the monometallic control. Essentially no difference in tacticity control is observed between these two complexes (37 % mmmm for the bimetallic complex; 35 % mmmm for the monometallic complex), indicating that the bimetallic environment of the dizirconium complex likely does not contribute to the tacticity control of these SiiPr3-substituted complexes. Both complexes shown good activity for ethylene homopolymerization with activities up to 6.1 kg mmolZr-1 h-1 when reactions were run over short periods of time. Lower activities at longer reaction times likely results from mass transport problems in the small-scale reactions.

column2: Work on the isolation and characterization of bimetallic (LSiPh3-L)Zr2 complexes is ongoing. Examination of the stereocontrol and activity of these complexes is of great interest in light of the promising behavior of their monometallic analogues.
New bimetallic and monometallic zirconium catalysts for olefin polymerization have been prepared at Caltech and tested for catalytic behavior at Caltech and KFUPM.

Para-terphenyl supported dizirconium complexes bearing bulk ortho-triisopropylsilyl and triphenylsilyl substituents were synthesized and the C2 symmetric isomer of (LSiiPr3-NMe2)Zr2 was characterized by single crystal X-Ray diffraction studies, confirming its identity. Initial polymerization results indicate that this new structurally-characterized bimetallic complex shows little difference in tacticity control from its monometallic control but has up to 10 x the activity in 1-hexene polymerization. Both monometallic and bimetallic complexes are promising catalysts for ethylene homopolymerization. Similar tacticity control between mono- and bimetallic complexes supports the original mechanistic proposal, given that bulky substituents would be expected to disfavor orientation of the polymer chain away from the central arene prior to coordination of the incoming monomer.
column3: Meta-terphenyl supported dizirconium complexes were prepared and characterized by 1H NMR and X-ray diffraction studies for one CS symmetric isomer of the (mLCl4-NMe2)Zr2 complex. Isolation of this and other isomers for polymerization has been challenging, so initial polymerizations have not been conducted. A series of C1 symmetric monometallic complexes bearing the same ortho substituents were also synthesized and complexes bearing triphenylsilyl substitution show promise for the synthesis of isotactically-enriched poly-1-hexene. In collaboration with the KFUPM team additional studies on homopolymerization and copolymerization by (LtBuSiiPr3-NMe2)Zr were conducted, indicating its promise as a catalyst for ethylene--olefin copolymerization.

column1: As future directions, the Caltech team will continue to prepare mono- and bimetallic catalyst precursors for olefin polymerization and oligomerization. Initial polymerization trials will be performed at Caltech, as previously done. The KFUPM team will perform polymerization trials under a wider set of conditions, and on larger scales. Homo- and copolymerizations will be performed with monomers including ethylene, propylene, and 1-hexene. The effects of reaction conditions such as temperature, amount of activator, additives (aluminum alkyl species), pressure, and reaction time on catalyst behavior will be studied at KFUPM. The use of the reactor available at KFUPM will allow for detail investigation of catalyst performance. The polymers will be characterized in detail at KFUPM. The Caltech team will also develop bimetallic catalysts for ethylene oligomerization. For these trials, methods for product characterization will be developed at KFUPM, followed by detailed studied of catalyst performance.

Initial synthetic experiments have been performed at Caltech for the synthesis of heterometallic precursors for hydrodesulfurization (HDS) catalysis. Complexes of MoM3 (M = Mn, Co) have been targeted, but these are challenging complexes to make and clean products have not been isolated to date. Further efforts will focus on developing synthetic protocols, employing various precursors, for the preparation of MoM3 clusters that will then be supported and sent to KFUPM for testing.
